Implement `src/parts/{{ lower_name }}.py`.

1. Use the Read tool to load `src/design.json`. Find the entry where `name == "{{ part_name }}"`. Note its `world_xyz`, `world_extents`, `geometry_strategy`, `color_rgba`, and any extra fields (`cavity`, `wall_thickness`, etc.).

2. Write `src/parts/{{ lower_name }}.py` with EXACTLY this top-level structure:

```
import bpy

def build_{{ lower_name }}():
    # ... your geometry code ...
    return obj   # obj.name MUST equal "{{ part_name }}"
```

If `design.json` includes a `"texture"` field for this part, ALSO define a sibling
function `texture_{{ lower_name }}(obj)` in the same file. The build harness calls
it after `build_{{ lower_name }}()` with the constructed object. See the SKILL
`topos_texture_creator` for procedural-vs-image patterns and UV unwrap details.
Failure inside `texture_*` is non-fatal — build.py logs and continues with flat material.

**Do NOT call `topos generate-texture` from Bash.** The framework dispatches a
separate `generate_texture_image` ToolTask per part (between your part task and
the build task) that materializes the PNG from `design.json[texture.prompt]`
into `design.json[texture.image_relpath]` BEFORE `texture_{{ lower_name }}(obj)`
runs at build time. Your job is only to write the `texture_{{ lower_name }}(obj)`
shader-binding code — for image textures, read the PNG path from design.json
and load it with `bpy.data.images.load`; if the file isn't there (texture
ToolTask failed), fall back to a flat material.

3. **Check for `instances` in your spec.** If `spec.get("instances")` is non-empty in design.json, your part is a **template** that build.py will duplicate. In that case:

   - Build the part's geometry **at the canonical pose only** — origin or `world_xyz`, no rotation, no per-instance shift. The build agent applies each instance's `rotation_euler` / `translation` after copying. Do NOT loop over instances inside your `build_{{ lower_name }}()`.
   - `world_xyz` / `world_extents` describe ONE instance's bbox — the canonical one. Sanity-check that.
   - One template ≠ one mesh per instance. Build the SHAPE; the build agent handles placement N times.
   - Anti-pattern: hard-coding 6 instances of geometry inside `build_fan_blade()` then expecting build.py to also instantiate 6. That gives 36 blades. The template builds ONE; build.py multiplies.

   If there's NO `instances` field, ignore this section — your part is a single-instance build.

4. Geometry contract — the returned obj's WORLD bbox must satisfy:
   - bbox center within 5mm of `world_xyz` (single-instance parts) OR centered at origin / canonical pose (instance template parts; build.py validates post-transform)
   - bbox extents (full width/depth/height along X/Y/Z) within 5mm of `world_extents`

